<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a JSON Web Token (JWT)?", answer: "A JSON Web Token (JWT) is a compact, URL-safe token format used for securely transmitting information between parties. It consists of three Base64-encoded parts separated by dots: a header (specifying the algorithm and token type), a payload (containing claims like user identity and expiration), and a signature (used to verify the token has not been tampered with)." },
  { question: "Is it safe to decode JWTs in the browser?", answer: "Yes, decoding a JWT is completely safe because the header and payload are simply Base64-encoded, not encrypted. Anyone with the token can read them. The security of a JWT comes from the signature, which proves the token was issued by a trusted party. This tool decodes the token but does not verify the signature, which requires the secret key or public key." },
  { question: "What are common JWT claims?", answer: "Standard JWT claims include: sub (subject - who the token is about), iss (issuer - who created the token), exp (expiration time as a Unix timestamp), iat (issued at - when the token was created), aud (audience - who the token is intended for), nbf (not before - token is not valid before this time), and jti (JWT ID - a unique identifier for the token)." },
  { question: "How do I know if a JWT is expired?", answer: "A JWT is expired when the current time is past the value in the exp (expiration) claim. The exp claim is a Unix timestamp representing the exact second when the token expires. This decoder automatically checks the expiration and tells you whether the token is still valid or has expired, along with the exact expiration date and time." },
  { question: "What is the difference between JWT decoding and verification?", answer: "Decoding a JWT means reading the header and payload by Base64-decoding them. Verification means checking that the signature is valid using the secret key (for HMAC algorithms) or the public key (for RSA/ECDSA algorithms). Decoding tells you what the token says; verification tells you whether the token is trustworthy. Never trust a JWT's contents without verifying the signature on the server side." }
]) %>

